Q9_OTHER_COMMENTS: "Being Dutch I feel inclined to defend the virtueus if Licorice (yes black)/Liquorish/Drop. Outside of this Geo-stratum you'd have a hard time finding quality drop.  Anywhere else it's just your American generic ""Haribo"" fake-ass ""drop"".  And for the last time: Red Liquorish is NOT drop.  Drop is to black liquorish as opium is to aspirin: very very weak. They have nothing to do with each other.  Admittedly, drop is an acquired taste, so I'd admit black liquorish may be called gateway drop. You know, for kids. (Not saying Dutch kids won't devour mouthfulls of the tar-black stuff, given half a chance. But then again, I've seen wine-drunk toddlers at camp-sites in France...)  Happy hallow's Eve'ryone!"

Q9_OTHER_COMMENTS: "When I was a kid, and lived in a Midwestern town of about 1100, Halloween was awe.some. I had 2 older sisters, and Mom would drop us off in town (we lived about a mile out) at dusk and tell us to meet at Grandma's (in town) at a certain time. Then we were turnt loose. Sisters always caught up with their older friends, and I made the rounds with mine. The streets were filled with kids, and no cars were out because everyone was home to greet the trick-r-treaters, except the local hoods TP-ing houses or rolling metal trashcans down the hill from the railroad tracks until it crashed into a parked car. Kids probably age 8-12 or so absolutely ruled the night. I ended up with a grocery bag of goods, and on the way home we always stopped at our neighbor's house, the widow Mrs. Strickler, who had been a teacher at the local high school until she retired in the 70s. She did not get many visitors, mostly people she knew and their kids, so she always had an amazing assortment: at least 2 full-size candy bars (Clark was a favorite) and *always* a caramel popcorn ball. Most years the elementary school hosted a Halloween Festival in the gymnasium, with a costume contest, ring toss, ""teacher jail"" (where you would pay a little money to put a teacher in a cardboard box painted to look like a jail cell, for 15 minutes or whatever), a haunted house in the locker room, and all proceeds went to I think the Lion's Club. One year when i was very young, I went as a paper sack of groceries.
